    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I usually open them with 7-Zip... It allows at least to see packages and classes and resources.<br>\nShould I need to see methods or fields, I would use Jad but of course, it is better to rely on (good) JavaDoc...</p>\n\n<p>Now, somewhere on SO was mentioned some Eclipse plug-ins, to find in which jar file a class is located, perhaps they can do more (ie. what you requested).</p>\n\n<p>[EDIT] Reference to SO thread. Not what is asked, but somehow related, thus useful: <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/275120/java-how-do-i-know-which-jar-file-to-use-given-a-class-name\" title=\"Java: How do I know which jar file to use given a class name?\">Java: How do I know which jar file to use given a class name?</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 9958,
      "reputation" : 11128,
      "user_id" : 18615,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 56,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5735c74e514d2e6b55ab65242c1ac6cf?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "M.N",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/18615/m-n"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 8,
    "last_activity_date" : 1227702421,
    "creation_date" : 1227702421,
    "answer_id" : 320529,
    "question_id" : 320510,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p><strong><a href=\"http://www.rarlab.com\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Use WinRar</a></strong>. It will open the folder structure for you in intact manner. Also allows in-archive editing, while preserving paths.</p>\n\n<p>Afterall, a JAR file is a ZIP archive only.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 14799,
      "reputation" : 4546,
      "user_id" : 30748,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a7af88ea1f8d6a8cfca5774ceaaef80f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Jeroen Heijmans",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/30748/jeroen-heijmans"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1227702501,
    "creation_date" : 1227702501,
    "answer_id" : 320537,
    "question_id" : 320510,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>Well, a jar-file is just a zip-file, so if you unzip it (with your favorite unzipping utility), you get all the files inside. </p>\n\n<p>If you want to look inside the class files to see the methods, you'll need a tool for that. As PhiLho mentions, Eclipse is able to do that (by default), and I would think most Java IDEs are capable of that.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3579,
      "reputation" : 54565,
