    "last_activity_date" : 1229863755,
    "creation_date" : 1229863755,
    "answer_id" : 384421,
    "question_id" : 320510,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>If I understand correctly, you want to see not only classes but also methods, properties and so on. The only tool I know that can do it is Eclipse - if you add a jar to project classpath, you would be able to browse its classes with methods and properties using usual package explorer.</p>\n\n<p>Anyway, this is a good idea for a good standalone Java tool</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 19314,
      "reputation" : 6820,
      "user_id" : 45163,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 86,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d8a7eea06d9bb16b3b168afc414a866d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Chris Nava",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/45163/chris-nava"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1229902192,
    "creation_date" : 1229902192,
    "answer_id" : 385183,
    "question_id" : 320510,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>I've set the default action in windows to \"Open with WinZip\".  This makes it easy to manage JARs as archives.  You can even add/remove files manually.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "user_type" : "does_not_exist",
      "display_name" : "John Doe"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 18,
    "last_activity_date" : 1244920042,
    "last_edit_date" : 1592644375,
    "creation_date" : 1244915387,
    "answer_id" : 991151,
    "question_id" : 320510,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<h3>Method names, fields, etc.</h3>\n<p>By adding a jar to a project in an IDE, you can usually see methods and field names, but not the detailed implementation. NetBeans can do it, Eclipse probably, IntelliJ probably, etc. You can browse the jar structure directly within the IDE.</p>\n<h3>Just the contents</h3>\n<p>For anything such as viewing the contents, you could use :</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>jar tvf jarfile.jar</code></li>\n<li>winzip or any zip tool</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>The source code</h3>\n<p>To access source code, you would use a decompiler such as JAD or one of its frontends or another decompiler. If the code is obfuscated, then ...</p>\n"
  }, {
