    "creation_date" : 1347627221,
    "answer_id" : 12425004,
    "question_id" : 320510,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>What I use personally is JD-GUI. It is a free 'decompiler', as it allows you to see the source code, classes, and objects in the classes, as well as see the file structure in a tree menu to the left. However, it does not allow  you to modify the classes directly.</p>\n\n<p>JD-GUI's website: <a href=\"http://jd.benow.ca/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">http://jd.benow.ca/</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1607070,
      "reputation" : 451,
      "user_id" : 1486944,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 86,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c86546b28d93cbfbb28047614558d614?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "james",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1486944/james"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1367563285,
    "last_edit_date" : 1367563285,
    "creation_date" : 1350495541,
    "answer_id" : 12940118,
    "question_id" : 320510,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you are in windows and using powershell and you are looking for a file in a jar you can do:</p>\n\n<pre><code>jar -tf .\\[JAR_NAME] | where {$_ -match \"[FILENAME]\"}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1395473,
      "reputation" : 730,
      "user_id" : 1325331,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/80a9d20c633d6d188dd5f78f8f132a7b?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Ziya",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1325331/ziya"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1352833842,
    "last_edit_date" : 1352833842,
    "creation_date" : 1352311955,
    "answer_id" : 13275618,
    "question_id" : 320510,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>One way to do this is to open the perspective in \"Package explorer\". Doing this you can see the structure of your jar with class details. For this check the library folder in your project using package explorer.</p>\n\n<p>Window>>Show View>>Other>>Java>>Package Explorer </p>\n\n<p>Another way  is, you can use JarPlug as a eclipse plugin. This works in eclipse/springsource</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://jar-plug.sourceforge.net/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://jar-plug.sourceforge.net/</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1911428,
      "reputation" : 189,
      "user_id" : 1725149,
      "user_type" : "registered",
