    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 5028364,
      "reputation" : 32504,
      "user_id" : 4039431,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 94,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/11cbc250ef94644843c0bf53bc752d74?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Amit",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4039431/amit"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 54,
    "last_activity_date" : 1567612774,
    "last_edit_date" : 1567612774,
    "creation_date" : 1487674376,
    "answer_id" : 42365315,
    "question_id" : 320510,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<blockquote>\n  <p>In case someone don't know this already, a JAR file is just a ZIP file\n  that contains the program's classes, resources, etc., and some\n  metadata. You can extract one to see how it's put together.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Hence I am using <code>unzip</code> command which is easy to remember and use.</p>\n\n<p><code>unzip -l &lt;jar-file-name&gt;.jar</code> </p>\n\n<p>For example, if you have a jar file with name <code>test.jar</code> then <code>unzip -l test.jar</code> will list all the content of jar file.</p>\n\n<p><strong>While all other answers are great, but in most of them, you would have to use some software like <code>7 zip</code> or <code>JDK</code> or some other eclipse tool while this doesn't require you to have any of these big s/w and it comes by default in linux and mac so its very lightweight and handy to use</strong>. </p>\n\n<p>You can also use <code>zipinfo &lt;your jar file&gt;</code>. if your OS supports this. </p>\n"
  }, {
