    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>java -xf some-j.jar</code> will unzip a JAR file.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3538154,
      "reputation" : 814,
      "user_id" : 2955930,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9f4bc325719109720e031915e364401f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Anil Kapoor",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2955930/anil-kapoor"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 34,
    "last_activity_date" : 1545297870,
    "last_edit_date" : 1545297870,
    "creation_date" : 1545297097,
    "answer_id" : 53865509,
    "question_id" : 320510,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<pre><code>jar -tvf file_name.jar\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>above will only <strong>print names of the files</strong>. </p>\n\n<p>To view the content of files, you can <strong>extract the files in a folder</strong> by:</p>\n\n<pre><code>jar -xvf file_name.jar\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>this will unzip jar file &amp; put the content in same directory where you are running this.</p>\n\n<p>Or in Windows rename .jar file to .zip &amp; then you can unzip to extract &amp; view the content of jar file. As jar is internally a zip file.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 9934627,
      "reputation" : 812,
      "user_id" : 7353353,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/335e8cd3378ab5f12a50fcdbe14d8b7a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Subhashree Pradhan",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/7353353/subhashree-pradhan"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1551785251,
    "creation_date" : 1551785251,
    "answer_id" : 55001762,
    "question_id" : 320510,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>My requirement was to view the content of a file (like a property file) inside the jar, without actually extracting the jar. If anyone reached this thread just like me, try this command -</p>\n\n<pre><code>unzip -p myjar.jar myfile.txt\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>This worked well for me!</p>\n"
  }, {
