    "body" : "<p>This <a href=\"http://dst.in.ua/jarexp/index.html?l=en\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Jar Explorer</a> is good enough. <br/>\nSupports three decompiler types: JD, Procyon and Fernflower.<br/>\nAllows to search files and duplicates in any java archive.<br/>\nAlso user can modify jar by D&amp;D files and edit some non-class files.\n<a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/y0Yxa.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/y0Yxa.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"></a>\n<a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/MSBPO.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/MSBPO.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"></a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 5816150,
      "reputation" : 53,
      "user_id" : 4585721,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/rXgB1.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Steven Broyles",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4585721/steven-broyles"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1583877381,
    "creation_date" : 1583877381,
    "answer_id" : 60626500,
    "question_id" : 320510,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>You can view JAR files like ZIP files from Windows Explorer by doing the following:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Run Command Prompt as Administrator</li>\n<li><p>From the command line, enter:</p>\n\n<p>assoc .jar=CompressedFolder</p></li>\n<li><p>While you are at it, you might as well do the same for WAR and EAR files:</p>\n\n<p>assoc .war=CompressedFolder</p>\n\n<p>assoc .ear=CompressedFolder</p></li>\n</ul>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 10147675,
      "reputation" : 129,
      "user_id" : 7495326,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a94fecc9033f2a39ce3c9485463d0b69?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "H&#252;seyin",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/7495326/h%c3%bcseyin"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1616570629,
    "creation_date" : 1616570629,
    "answer_id" : 66776379,
    "question_id" : 320510,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Easiest way to view classes, methods, properties, etc. inside a jar file is using programs like '<a href=\"https://www.win-rar.com/start.html?&amp;L=5\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">winrar</a>' and '<a href=\"https://www.7-zip.org/download.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">7-Zip</a>'.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Download winrar or 7-zip program if it's not installed</li>\n<li>Then right click to your jar file</li>\n<li>Click open with winrar or 7-zip</li>\n</ul>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 369969,
      "reputation" : 22590,
      "user_id" : 717630,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c891f554b48ea8c4bb1b11873450c945?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "grepit",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/717630/grepit"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1620249366,
    "creation_date" : 1620249366,
    "answer_id" : 67408824,
    "question_id" : 320510,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Most people have answered this correctly here is one solution for linux if you don't even know where your jar path is or your JDK path is different on each host</p>\n<pre><code>$(find / -type f -name &quot;jar&quot; 2&gt;&amp;1 |grep '/JDK' |head -1 ) tf FULLY_QUALIFIED_NAME_TO_YOUR_FILE\n</code></pre>\n"
  } ],
